{"product_links": "https://www.beautypedia.com/products/eye-elements-baked-eyeshadow-highlighter-quad/?archive_search=%2Fmakeup%2Feyes%2Feyeshadow-reviews%2F%3Fsize%3D96%26makeup_group%5B0%5D%3Deyeshadow-reviews%26p%3D2 ", "product_names": "Eye Elements Baked Eyeshadow & Highlighter Quad", "category": "Eye Makeup", "sub_category": "Eyeshadow", "brand": "Laura Geller", "ingredient": "", "size": "", "price": "38.00", "claims": null, "image_url": "https://www.beautypedia.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/1E0226FE-C36E-42E8-81AA-7A3C21730EC8_5112Ej7L3RL.jpg?w=369", "expert_rating": "2", "expert_reviews": ["Eye Elements Baked Eyeshadow & Highlighter Quad offers the convenience of having a multi-use highlighter and eyeshadow trio combined in one compact. Expect a shiny, dry, powder finish because this is a mineral product with mica and talc as its two main ingredients.", "It applies sheer but builds well if you want more intensity. The finish is quite shiny, and, for the most part, the color combinations are workable for fair to deep skin tones\u2014the highlighters come in soft gold and peachy shades, and they\u2019re paired with eyeshadow trios in a range of eggplant purples or slate gray/blue combinations. The two sets to avoid are Sand & Sea and Meadow Skies, both of which offer unflattering, difficult-to-work-with color combinations for any skin tone.", "Other than the interesting setup of this compact, there is nothing that sets it apart from other \"baked\" mineral eyeshadows (not to mention the whole concept of mineral makeup is silly because most of the ingredients in any powder qualify as \"mineral\"). Labeling the larger section of this compact as a \"highlighter\" to be used on cheeks\u2014as well as eyes\u2014is simply an application suggestion. The formula and shiny finish are the same for all four shades in the quad.", "Pros:", "Cons:"], "expert_pros": null, "expert_cons": null, "jar_package": null, "animal_test": null, "user_rating": null, "product_id": 685}
