{"product_links": "https://www.beautypedia.com/products/baked-eye-color/?archive_search=%2Fmakeup%2Feyes%2Feyeshadow-reviews%2F%3Fsize%3D96%26makeup_group%5B0%5D%3Deyeshadow-reviews%26p%3D2 ", "product_names": "Baked Eye Color", "category": "Eye Makeup", "sub_category": "Eyeshadow", "brand": "The Body Shop", "ingredient": null, "size": "", "price": "13.00", "claims": null, "image_url": "https://www.beautypedia.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DA46B5C9-BDA0-4BCB-95F4-2CFE9639E349_TheBodyShopBakedEyeColor.jpg?w=853", "expert_rating": "2", "expert_reviews": ["This shimmery pressed-powder eyeshadow offers two marbleized shades in one compact, without a divider. The eight shades available consist of shimmer-rich jewel and earth tones. The texture is soft, making it easy to apply and blend, but depending on the depth of color you\u2019re looking for, you may be disappointed with how sheer this shadow is. In short, you\u2019ll see more shimmer than color, but the shimmer stays put with minimal flaking.", "Although the dome-shaped powder offers a generous amount of product, several compacts on the store shelves already had crumbled to pieces before opening, which is a problem for \u201cbaked\u201d press powders. So, if you decide to buy, you\u2019ll want to handle this pressed-powder eyeshadow with care."], "expert_pros": null, "expert_cons": null, "jar_package": null, "animal_test": null, "user_rating": null, "product_id": 708}
{"product_links": "https://www.beautypedia.com/products/shimmering-cream-eye-color/?archive_search=%2Fmakeup%2Feyes%2Feyeshadow-reviews%2F%3Fsize%3D96%26makeup_group%5B0%5D%3Deyeshadow-reviews%26p%3D2 ", "product_names": "Shimmering Cream Eye Color", "category": "Eye Makeup", "sub_category": "Eyeshadow", "brand": "Shiseido", "ingredient": "Water (Aqua),  Dimethicone,  Polymethylsilsesquioxane,  Mica,  Dipropylene Glycol,  Titanium Dioxide (Ci 77891),  Paraffin,  Sorbitan Sesquiisostearate,  Peg-10 Dimethicone,  Microcrystalline Wax (Cera Microcristallina),  Glycerin,  Phenoxyethanol,  Silica,  Iron Oxides (Ci 77492),  Iron Oxides (Ci 77491),  Sodium Dehydroacetate,  Distearyldimonium Chloride,  Palmitic Acid,  Silica Dimethyl Silylate,  Carmine (Ci 75470),  Tocopherol, Tocopheryl Acetate,  Isopropyl Alcohol,  Polysilicone-2,  Polyacrylate-4,  Peg/Ppg-36/41 Dimethyl Ether,  Lavandula Angustifolia (Lavender) Oil,  Ultramarines (Ci 77007),  Iron Oxides (Ci 77499),  Dipentaerythrityl Hexahydroxystearate,  Methicone,  Zinc Oxide,  Tetradecene. NOTE: Ingredients may vary by shade from the above listing.", "size": "", "price": "25.00", "claims": null, "image_url": "https://www.beautypedia.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/C2973D94-4136-421F-B066-49A4181B0332_31Tb2WmtCCL.jpg?w=300", "expert_rating": "1", "expert_reviews": ["This cream-to-powder eyeshadow is housed in a glass jar with a screw-on lid. Its texture is silky and each shade is highly pigmented\u2014talk about a shock of color! A little goes a long way and several of the shades work great to add depth or highlight the eye area.", "Speaking of the shades, each has sparkling shine that's attractive without being overly shiny. The colors themselves are a mixed bag; some are brilliant while others are too bold or difficult to work with (but are fine if you want a colorful eye design). Favorites include BK912, SV810, BR306, and BR709.", "In terms of longevity, once the formula sets it stays put quite well; no smudging, smearing, or fading was noticed\u2014and these take some effort to remove (have an oil- or silicone-based makeup remover handy).", "All told, this is a stellar product, except for the fact that it contains lavender oil, which can be a potent skin irritant and is absolutley not something that should be applied around the eyes. See More Info for details; this ingedient is solely responsible for the rating assigned.", "More Info:", "Research indicates that components of lavender, specifically linalool, can be cytotoxic, which means that topical application causes skin-cell death (Source: Cell Proliferation, June 2004, pages 221\u2013229). Lavender leaves contain camphor, which is a known skin irritant. Because the fragrance constituents in lavender oil oxidize when exposed to air, lavender oil is a pro-oxidant, and this enhanced oxidation increases its irritancy on skin (Source: Contact Dermatitis, September 2008, pages 143\u2013150). Lavender oil is the most potent form, and even small amounts of it (0.25% or less) are problematic. Although it\u2019s fine as an aromatherapy agent for inhalation or relaxation, it is a must to avoid in skin-care products. (Sources: Psychiatry Research, February 2007, pages 89\u201396; and www.naturaldatabase.com)."], "expert_pros": null, "expert_cons": null, "jar_package": null, "animal_test": null, "user_rating": null, "product_id": 709}
